{"displayTopicName":"Hebrew definite article","topicTokens":[{"text":"Hebrew definite article","type":"text"}],"paragraphsBySubtopic":{"Hebrew definite article":[{"text":"Hebrew has something called a definite article, as do many languages.\n(The definite article in English is the word “the.”)\nDefinite articles are used to refer to things that are already known to the reader.\n","type":"text"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":"right","rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"More","type":"local","tokens":[{"text":"More","type":"text"}],"targetSubtopic":"More","targetTopic":"Hebrew definite article","enclosingTopic":"Hebrew definite article","enclosingSubtopic":"Hebrew definite article"}]}]}],"More":[{"text":"In Hebrew, the definite article is a ה-prefix before a noun, usually pronounced הַ, ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"ha","type":"text"}]},{"text":", e.g. as in הַכֶּלֶב, ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"hakelev","type":"text"}]},{"text":", “the dog.”\nThe term in Hebrew for “definite article” is ה\"א הַיְּדִיעָה, ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"hay hayediah","type":"text"}]},{"text":", literally “the hay of knowledge,” i.e. because it is used to refer to something that is already known to the reader.\nSometimes, the הַ gets combined with ","type":"text"},{"text":"the prefix ב","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"the prefix ב","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Prefix_ב","enclosingTopic":"Hebrew definite article","enclosingSubtopic":"More"},{"text":" or ","type":"text"},{"text":"the prefix ל","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"the prefix ל","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Prefix_ל","enclosingTopic":"Hebrew definite article","enclosingSubtopic":"More"},{"text":", and becomes a בַ or לַ, meaning e.g. “in the” or “to the.” For example, adding ב before הַבַּיִת (","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"habayis","type":"text"}]},{"text":", “the house”) becomes בַּבַּיִת (","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"babayis","type":"text"}]},{"text":" “in the house,” as opposed to ","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"b’bayis","type":"text"}]},{"text":", “in a house.”)\nAramaic also has a definite article, but it is an א-suffix not a ה-prefix, as in עָלְמָ","type":"text"},{"type":"bold","tokens":[{"text":"א","type":"text"}]},{"text":" (","type":"text"},{"type":"italics","tokens":[{"text":"alma,","type":"text"}]},{"text":" “the world.”) ","type":"text"},{"text":"<small>→</small>","type":"global","tokens":[{"type":"html_element","tokenInsertions":[],"html":"<small>→</small>"}],"pathString":"Aramaic_definite_article","enclosingTopic":"Hebrew definite article","enclosingSubtopic":"More"},{"text":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"table_list","alignment":"right","rtl":false,"items":[{"list":false,"hidden":false,"tokens":[{"text":"Back","type":"global","tokens":[{"text":"Back","type":"text"}],"pathString":"Hebrew_definite_article#Hebrew_definite_article","enclosingTopic":"Hebrew definite article","enclosingSubtopic":"More"}]}]}]}}